    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.20.13-16_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">13</fw>
                
                <note type="authorial">I want to write Sigurd. Is "c/o La Guardia Field, <hi rend="caps">N.Y.C.</hi>" all right?</note>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <note type="curatorial">Lafayette, Indiana</note>
                
                        Tuesday
                        10/6/42
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Gaki,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>You're as prompt in your return as a new handball! Thanks. I'll get off the Macmillan letter tomorrow (Helen's filling the house with about eight other people this evening &#8212; for gobble, gobble gobble, and git &#8212; and I must go in a moment to remove the traces of my long day at the desk). I'll be glad to have a word in at headquarters.</p>
                
                <p>I felt closer than ever to you today. Some of my time had to go in the service of <unclear>Marmnon</unclear> (alias Bread <hi rend="caps">N.</hi> Butter), but I managed about 4 1/2-5 hours with Chittenden, with side glances into a couple of related volumes (<hi rend="underline">Astoria</hi> + <hi rend="underline">Bonneville</hi>, which I shall read completely a bit later of course). The way papers shower on me I'm almost constantly in a condition of damp spirits. I'm (Mona's not listening is she?) goddamned tired of the trivial mechanics of freshman tests and themes, but               
                    
                    <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.20.13-16_0002"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">14</fw>
                        
                    how can one escape this necessary preliminary work? Less said of this the better! When we shake ourselves down into some outdoors clothes and snort westword (I <hi rend="underline">mean</hi> "snort"&#8212;man, I'll
                    
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.20.13-16_0003"/> 
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
                    
                    <unclear>be</unclear> blowing like a stallion!), however, you'll find me hard to hold. The reaction from my present imprisonment of the spirit and flesh will be as violent as the recoil of a coast defense rifle.</p>
                    
                <p>Pard, you're shore layin' it on that pore feller Askins! He's 'bout dead now, I reckon, but hold the rest o' yore fire till I find a place fer the body. I thought your (dialect's off) letter felt hot, and sure enough, when I opened it a definite wisp of smoke lazed out. Careful now!</p> 
                    
                <p>My Sunday letter contained word about the matter of shells, but today I must take you up on the <unclear>ramrod</unclear>. I'd be glad to have it, of course (all I can get here is <hi rend="underline">Quin sabe</hi>?'s), <hi rend="underline">if</hi> it is long enough for my 28-inch rifle barrel plus four inches for the bolt passage (about 32 inches of rod), and <hi rend="underline">if</hi> you will tell me its cost to you so that I might reimburse you. <hi rend="caps">OK</hi>? About sending it: if not inconvenient, right away; if preferable, when you send the 10 boxes or so of shells a few weeks hence. Bless you!</p>
               
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.20.13-16_0004"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">16</fw>
                
                <p>A gorgeous cool day here today. I felt the call of rifle and outdoors but gritted my remaining molars and stayed indoors. I can think of you and your dears just as well here as somewhere else!</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Our heart's best to you.</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Alvin</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
